05975nam a22007455i 9789048505401DE-B159720221201113901.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221201t20052005ne     fo  d z      eng d  a97890485054017 a10.1515/97890485054012doi  a(DE-B1597)532928  a(OCoLC)1084280053  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anecNL 7aPER0000002bisacsh04a306.8500aShooting the Family :bTransnational Media and Intercultural Values /ced. by Patricia Pisters, Wim Staat. 1aAmsterdam : bAmsterdam University Press, c[2005] 4c©2005  a1 online resource (224 p.) :bIllustrated  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- tPart 1: The Family and the Media -- t1. Capturing the Family: Home Video in the Age of Digital Reproduction -- t2. Migrant Children Mediating Family Relations -- t3. The Shooting Family: Gender and Ethnicity in the New Dutch Police Series -- tPart 2: Private Matters, Public Families -- t4. Family Portrait: Queering the Nuclear Family in François Ozon's Sitcom -- t5. Radicalism Begins at Home: Fundamentalism and the Family in My Son the Fanatic -- t6. Family Matters in Eat Drink Man Woman: Food Envy, Family Longing, or Intercultural Knowledge through the Senses? -- tPart 3: Translating Family Values -- t7. Saved by Betrayal? Ang Lee's Translations of "Chinese" Family Ideology -- t8. Eurydice's Diasporic Voice: Marcel Camus's Black Orpheus and the Family in Poet's Hell -- t9. Archiving the (Secret) Family in Egoyan's Family Viewing -- tPart 4: Loving Families -- t10. Suspending the Body: Biopower and the Contradictions of Family Values -- t11. Unfamiliar Film: Sisters Unsettling Family Habits -- t12. Micropolitics of the Migrant Family in Accented Cinema: Love and Creativity in Empire -- tList of Contributors -- tIndex0 aOpen Accessuhttps://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_abf2funrestricted online access2star  aShooting the Family, a collection of essays on the contemporary media landscape, explores ever-changing representations of family life on a global scale. The contributors argue that new recording technologies allows families an unusual kind of freedom-until now unknown-to define and respond to their own lives and memories. Recently released videos made by young émigrés as they discover new homelands and resolve conflicts with their parents, for example, reverberate alongside the dark portrayals of family life in the formal filmmaking of Ang Lee. This book will be a boon to scholars of film theory and media studies, as well as to anyone interested in the construction of the family in a postmodern world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0https://www.aup.nl/en/publish/open-access  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aFamilies. 0aMass media and families. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / General.2bisacsh1 aBaronian, Marie-Aude, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBruin, Joost de, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCopier, Laura, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDasgupta, Sudeep, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDijck, José van, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHermes, Joke, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKloet, Jeroen de, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKooijman, Jaap, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLaine, Tarja, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLeeuw, Sonja de, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLord, Catherine M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc